The Republic | azcentral.comDozens of customs officers guard a railroad crossing east of the San Ysidro crossing in San Diego, following Sunday's attempt by groups of migrants to rush the border.
(Photo: Rafael Carranza, The Republic)U.S. officials say the number of active-duty troops on the border with Mexico will drop from 5,600 to about 4,000, and their deployment will be extended through the end of January.
Officials say the Department of Homeland Security submitted a formal request for the additional military support Friday.
But military officials have been working with Homeland Security for weeks to help craft a request that would be accepted by the Pentagon.
President Donald Trump deployed the troops to the border in response to a caravan of migrants walking to the U.S. from Central America.